<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,621,767]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,621,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Chandler, 1994" authorityName="Chandler" authorityYear="1994" box="[586,910,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Xenoplatyura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="autumna">
<emphasis box="[586,722,621,646]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">X. autumna</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler" box="[730,910,621,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="37" refString="Chandler, P. J. (1994) The fungus gnats of Israel (Diptera: Sciaroidea, excluding Sciaridae). Israel Journal of Entomology 28: 1 - 100." type="journal article" year="1994">
Chandler, 
<quantity box="[851,910,621,647]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.06476" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" unit="in" value="1994.0">1994</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in having a faint dark shade at apex of wing and the shape of tergite IX. However, it is easily distinguished by the distance between tips of R 
<number box="[1329,1339,661,687]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" value="1.0">1</number>
and R 
<number box="[1422,1436,661,687]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" value="4.0">4</number>
being 
<number box="[223,312,701,727]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" value="1.7000000000000002" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.6">1.6–1.8</number>
times as long as R 
<number box="[533,547,701,727]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" value="4.0">4</number>
(
<number box="[564,602,701,727]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" value="0.3">0.3</number>
times in 
<taxonomicName box="[710,845,701,726]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Xenoplatyura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="autumna">
<emphasis box="[710,845,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="32">X. autumna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The shape of gonocoxites and gonostyli are also good characters to distinguish it from the other three Chinese species of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
